          <summary class="faq-question">Is it free?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>Yes, 100% free and open source.</strong> The code is available on GitHub under the <a href="/licence">EUPL 1.2</a> license.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Do I need to buy a new keyboard?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>No.</strong> AZERTY Global is a purely software solution. It works with your current keyboard.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Is it compatible with games (ZQSD)?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>Yes.</strong> The physical Z, Q, S, D keys don't move. Your games work exactly as before.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Available on Mac and Linux?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>Yes!</strong> AZERTY Global is available on <strong>Windows</strong> (10 and 11 recommended; earlier versions supported on a legacy basis, depending on the channel), <strong>macOS</strong> (10.12+) and <strong>Linux</strong> (Ubuntu, Debian, Fedora, Arch...).</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">How long does it take to adjust?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>A few hours.</strong> Only 5 changes, less than 1% of your keystrokes will be different.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Who created AZERTY Global?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p><strong>Antoine Olivier</strong>. He created AZERTY Global in 2017 when he was a student in a French preparatory class, frustrated by the impossibility of typing correctly in French on his keyboard. The project is now carried by the AMCF (Association pour la Modernisation du Clavier Français) and remains volunteer-run.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

